blocks.name: df-ram
blocks.content: Define the Ramsey number function. The input is a number ` m ` for the size of the edges of the hypergraph, and a tuple ` r ` from the finite color set to lower bounds for each color. The Ramsey number ` ( M Ramsey R ) ` is the smallest number such that for any set ` S ` with ` ( M Ramsey R ) <_ # S ` and any coloring ` F ` of the set of ` M ` -element subsets of ` S ` (with color set ` dom R ` ), there is a color ` c e. dom R ` and a subset ` x C_ S ` such that ` R ( c ) <_ # x ` and all the hyperedges of ` x ` (that is, subsets of ` x ` of size ` M ` ) have color ` c ` . (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 20-Apr-2015.) (Revised by AV, 14-Sep-2020.)

blocks.name: ramub2
blocks.content: It is sufficient to check the Ramsey property on finite sets of size equal to the upper bound. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 23-Apr-2015.)

blocks.name: ramxrcl
blocks.content: The Ramsey number is an extended real number. (This theorem does not imply Ramsey's theorem, unlike ~ ramcl .) (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 20-Apr-2015.)

blocks.name: ramubcl

blocks.name: ramub1
blocks.content: Inductive step for Ramsey's theorem, in the form of an explicit upper bound. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 23-Apr-2015.)
blocks.origin:
thm ramub1(setvar s0, setvar s1, class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, wff w0) {
  |- wi(w0, wbr(co(c0, cram, c1), cle, co(co(co(c0, cmin, nat1), cram, c2), caddc, nat1)))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c0, cn))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c3, cfn))
  -| wi(w0, wf(c1, c3, cn))
  -| wceq(c2, cmpt(s0, c3, co(c0, cram, cmpt(s1, c3, cif(co(cfv(c1, cv(s0)), cmin, nat1), cfv(c1, cv(s1)), wceq(cv(s1), cv(s0)))))))
  -| wi(w0, wf(c2, c3, cn0))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(co(co(c0, cmin, nat1), cram, c2), cn0))
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffsc(s0, c0)
  -| diffsc(s0, c1)
  -| diffsc(s0, c2)
  -| diffsc(s0, c3)
  -| diffsc(s1, c0)
  -| diffsc(s1, c1)
  -| diffsc(s1, c2)
  -| diffsc(s1, c3)
  -| diffsw(s0, w0)
  -| diffsw(s1, w0)
} = {
  ramub2(hs1, hs2, hs3, hs5, hs4, hs6, hs0, c0, c1, co(co(co(c0, cmin, nat1), cram, c2), caddc, nat1), cmpo(hs1, hs2, universe, cn0, crab(hs3, cpw(cv(hs1)), wceq(cfv(chash, cv(hs3)), cv(hs2)))), c3, cfn, w0)
  nnnn0d(c0, w0)
  sylancl(w0, wf(c1, c3, cn0), wf(c1, c3, cn), wss(cn, cn0))
  nnssnn0()
  fss(c1, c3, cn, cn0)
  syl(w0, wcel(co(co(co(c0, cmin, nat1), cram, c2), caddc, nat1), cn0), wcel(co(co(c0, cmin, nat1), cram, c2), cn0))
  peano2nn0(co(co(c0, cmin, nat1), cram, c2))
  mpd(wa(w0, wa(wceq(cfv(chash, cv(hs5)), co(co(co(c0, cmin, nat1), cram, c2), caddc, nat1)), wf(cv(hs4), co(cv(hs5), cmpo(hs1, hs2, universe, cn0, crab(hs3, cpw(cv(hs1)), wceq(cfv(chash, cv(hs3)), cv(hs2)))), c0), c3))), wrex(hs6, c3, wrex(hs0, cpw(cv(hs5)), wa(wbr(cfv(c1, cv(hs6)), cle, cfv(chash, cv(hs0))), wss(co(cv(hs0), cmpo(hs1, hs2, universe, cn0, crab(hs3, cpw(cv(hs1)), wceq(cfv(chash, cv(hs3)), cv(hs2)))), c0), cima(ccnv(cv(hs4)), csn(cv(hs6))))))), wex(hs7, wcel(cv(hs7), cv(hs5))))

blocks.name: ramcl
blocks.content: Ramsey's theorem: the Ramsey number is an integer for every finite coloring and set of upper bounds. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 23-Apr-2015.)

blocks.name: ramsey
blocks.content: Ramsey's theorem with the definition ` Ramsey ` eliminated. If ` M ` is an integer, ` R ` is a specified finite set of colors, and ` F : R --> NN0 ` is a set of lower bounds for each color, then there is an ` n ` such that for every set ` s ` of size greater than ` n ` and every coloring ` f ` of the set ` ( s C M ) ` of all ` M ` -element subsets of ` s ` , there is a color ` c ` and a subset ` x C_ s ` such that ` x ` is larger than ` F ( c ) ` and the ` M ` -element subsets of ` x ` are monochromatic with color ` c ` . This is the hypergraph version of Ramsey's theorem; the version for simple graphs is the case ` M = 2 ` . This is Metamath 100 proof #31. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 23-Apr-2015.)
